 cyclone}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|ITC}}|{{Sort|215|215&nbsp;km/h (130&nbsp;mph)}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|ITC}}|{{Sort|0934|934&nbsp;hPa (27.58&nbsp;inHg)}} || [[Seychelles]], Madagascar, [[Comoros]], Mozambique, Tanzania, Malawi || \u2265{{ntsp|100000000||$}} || {{nts|52}}|| <ref name=\"Comoros report 2\" /><ref name=\"April 2019 report\" />\n|-\n| {{Sort|15|Lorna}} || {{Sort|190421|April&nbsp;21&nbsp;\u2013 May&nbsp;1}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|TC}}|{{Sort|5|Tropical cyclone}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|TC}}|{{Sort|150|150&nbsp;km/h (90&nbsp;mph)}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|TC}}|{{Sort|0964|964&nbsp;hPa (28.47&nbsp;inHg)}} || None || {{ntsh|0}} None || {{ntsh|0}} None || \n|-\n{{TC Areas affected (Bottom)|TC's=15&nbsp;systems|dates=September 13 \u2013 May 1|winds=215&nbsp;km/h (130&nbsp;mph)|pres=934&nbsp;hPa (27.58&nbsp;inHg)|damage=\u2265$2.311&nbsp;billion|deaths=1,382|Refs=}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*Tropical cyclones in [[Tropical cyclones in 2018|2018]] and [[Tropical cyclones in 2019|2019]]\n*[[List of Southern Hemisphere cyclone seasons]]\n*Atlantic hurricane seasons: [[2018 Atlantic hurricane season|2018]], [[2019 Atlantic hurricane season|2019]]\n*Pacific hurricane seasons: [[2018 Pacific hurricane season|2018]], [[2019 Pacific hurricane season|2019]]\n*Pacific typhoon seasons: [[2018 Pacific typhoon season|2018]], [[2019 Pacific typhoon season|2019]]\n*North Indian Ocean cyclone seasons: [[2018 North Indian Ocean cyclone season|2018]], [[2019 North Indian Ocean cyclone season|2019]]\n*[[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season]]\n*[[2018\u201319 South Pacific cyclone season]]\n*[[1999\u20132000 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]] \u2013 The third-deadliest South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|2018-19 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season}}\n* [http://www.meteofrance.re M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France La R\u00e9union] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.meteomadagascar.mg Direction G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la M\u00e9t\u00e9orologie de Madagascar] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://metservice.intnet.mu Mauritius Meteorological Services]\n* [http://www.metoc.navy.mil/jtwc/jtwc.html Joint Typhoon Warning Center (JTWC)]\n\n{{2018\u201319 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season buttons}}\n{{TC Decades|Year=2010|basin=South-West Indian Ocean|type=cyclone|shem=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2018-19 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season}}\n[[Category:2018\u201319 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season]]\n[[Category:South-West Indian Ocean cyclone seasons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hurricane season \n| Basin=SWI\n| Year=2019\n| Track=2018-2019 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season summary.png\n| First storm formed=September 13, 2018\n| Last storm dissipated=May 1, 2019\n| Strongest storm name=[[Cyclone Kenneth|Kenneth]]\n| Strongest storm pressure=934\n| Strongest storm winds=115\n| Average wind speed=10\n| Total disturbances=15\n| Total depressions=15\n| Total storms=15 <small>(record high)</small>\n| Total hurricanes=11 <small>(record high)</small>\n| Total intense=10 <small>(record high)</small>\n| Total super=\n| Fatalities=1,382 total<br><small>(Deadliest South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season on record)</small>\n| Damagespre=\u2265\n| Damages=2311\n| Damagespost=<small>Costliest South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season on record</small>\n| five seasons=[[2016\u201317 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season|2017\u201318]], '''2018\u201319''', [[2019\u201320 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season|2019\u201320]], ''[[Lists of tropical cyclone names|2020\u201321]]''\n| Australian season=2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season\n| South Indian season=2018\u201319 South Pacific cyclone season\n}}\nThe '''2018\u201319 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season''' was the costliest and the most active season ever recorded since reliable records began in 1967. Additionally, it is also the deadliest cyclone season recorded in the South-West Indian Ocean, surpassing the [[List of South-West Indian Ocean cyclones before 1959|1891\u201392 season]], in which the [[1892 Mauritius cyclone]] devastated the island of [[Mauritius]].<ref name=\"extreme catastrophe\">{{cite web |last1=Masters |first1=Jeff |title=Africa\u2019s Hurricane Katrina: Tropical Cyclone Idai Causes an Extreme Catastrophe |url=https://www.wunderground.com/cat6/Africas-Hurricane-Katrina-Tropical-Cyclone-Idai-Causes-Extreme-Catastrophe |website=Weather Underground |accessdate=23 March 2019}}</ref> The season was an event of the annual cycle of [[tropical cyclone]] and [[subtropical cyclone]] formation in the South-West Indian Ocean basin. It officially began on November 15, 2018, and ended on April 30, 2019, with the exception for [[Mauritius]] and the [[Seychelles]], which it ended on May 15, 2019. These dates conventionally delimit the period of each year when most tropical and subtropical cyclones form in the basin, which is west of [[longitude|90\u00b0E]] and south of the [[Equator]]. Tropical and subtropical cyclones in this basin are monitored by the [[Regional Specialised Meteorological Centre]] in [[R\u00e9union]]. \n\nThe first tropical cyclone was an unnamed moderate tropical storm that formed northeast of [[Madagascar]] on September 13, 2018, two months before the official start of the season. Two cyclones formed in the month of November, with Intense Tropical Cyclone Alcide forming on November 5, and Severe Tropical Storm Bouchra entering the basin from the Australian region on November 9. Two tropical cyclones formed in the month of December, Cilida and Kenanga. Intense Tropical Cyclone Kenanga crossed into the basin from the [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season|Australian region]], retaining its name assigned by [[TCWC Jakarta]]. Two moderate tropical storms formed in January, Desmond and Eketsang. Five more intense tropical cyclones formed during February and March: Funani, Gelena, Haleh, [[Cyclone Idai|Idai]], and Joaninha. In addition, Savannah crossed into the basin from the Australian basin as an intense tropical cyclone in March. Of these storms, all of them but Haleh and Savannah produced impacts on land, with Idai causing at least 1,303 deaths and US$2.2&nbsp;billion in damages in [[Mozambique]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Malawi]], and [[Madagascar]].<ref name=\"damages at 2 billion\" /><ref name=\"devastation\" /><ref name=\"emdat\"/> The season set a new record of ten intense tropical cyclones, the largest number since the start of reliable satellite coverage in 1967, surpassing the [[2006\u201307 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season|2006\u201307]] season.\n\n__TOC__\n{{clear}}\n\n==Seasonal summary==\n<center>\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:800 height:215\nPlotArea  = top:10 bottom:80 right:20 left:20\nLegend    = columns:3 left:30 top:58 columnwidth:250\nAlignBars  = early\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/09/2018 till:31/05/2019\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal\nScaleMinor = grid:black unit:month increment:1 start:01/09/2018\nColors     =\n  id:canvas value:gray(0.88)\n  id:GP   value:red\n  id:ZD   value:rgb(0.5,0.8,1)   legend:Zone_of_Disturbed_Weather/Tropical_Disturbance\n  id:TD   value:rgb(0.38,0.73,1) legend:Tropical_Depression\n  id:TS   value:rgb(0,0.98,0.96) legend:Moderate_Tropical_Storm\n  id:ST   value:rgb(0.80,1,1)    legend:Severe_Tropical_Storm\n  id:TC   value:rgb(1,1,0.80)    legend:Tropical_Cyclone\n  id:IT   value:rgb(1,0.76,0.25) legend:Intense_Tropical_Cyclone\n  id:VI   value:rgb(1,0.38,0.38) legend:Very_Intense_Tropical_Cyclone\n\nBackgroundcolors = canvas:canvas\n\nBarData =\n  barset:Hurricane\n  bar:Month\n\nPlotData=\n  barset:Hurricane width:11 align:left fontsize:S shift:(4,-4) anchor:till\n  from:13/09/2018 till:17/09/2018 color:TS text:\"01\"\n  from:05/11/2018 till:12/11/2018 color:IT text:\"Alcide\"\n  from:09/11/2018 till:09/11/2018 color:ZD\n  barset:break\n  barset:skip\n  barset:skip\n  from:10/11/2018 till:12/11/2018 color:ST\n  barset:break\n  barset:skip\n  barset:skip\n  from:13/11/2018 till:13/11/2018 color:ZD\n  barset:break\n  barset:skip\n  barset:skip\n  from:16/11/2018 till:19/11/2018 color:ST text:\"Bouchra\"\n  from:16/12/2018 till:22/12/2018 color:IT text:\"Kenanga\"\n  from:16/12/2018 till:24/12/2018 color:IT text:\"Cilida\"\n  from:17/01/2019 till:22/01/2019 color:TS text:\"Desmond\"\n  from:22/01/2019 till:24/01/2019 color:TS text:\"Eketsang\"\n  from:03/02/2019 till:10/02/2019 color:IT text:\"Funani\"\n  barset:break\n  from:04/02/2019 till:14/02/2019 color:IT text:\"Gelena\"\n  from:28/02/2019 till:07/03/2019 color:IT text:\"Haleh\"\n  from:04/03/2019 till:16/03/2019 color:IT text:\"[[Cyclone Idai|Idai]]\"\n  from:17/03/2019 till:19/03/2019 color:IT text:\"[[Cyclone Savannah|Savannah]]\"\n  from:18/03/2019 till:30/03/2019 color:IT text:\"Joaninha\"\n  from:21/04/2019 till:29/04/2019 color:IT text:\"[[Cyclone Kenneth|Kenneth]]\"\n  from:21/04/2019 till:01/05/2019 color:TC text:\"Lorna\"\n\n  bar:Month width:5 align:center fontsize:S shift:(0,-20) anchor:middle color:canvas\n  from:01/09/2018 till:01/10/2018 text:September\n  from:01/10/2018 till:01/11/2018 text:October\n  from:01/11/2018 till:01/12/2018 text:November\n  from:01/12/2018 till:31/12/2018 text:December\n  from:01/01/2019 till:31/01/2019 text:January\n  from:01/02/2019 till:28/02/2019 text:February\n  from:01/03/2019 till:31/03/2019 text:March\n  from:01/04/2019 till:30/04/2019 text:April\n  from:01/05/2019 till:31/05/2019 text:May\n\nTextData =\n   pos:(525,23)\n   text:\"(For further details, please see\"\n   pos:(672,23)\n   text:\"[[Tropical_cyclone_scales#Comparisons_across_basins|scales]])\"\n</timeline>\n</center>\nThe season officially began on November 15, 2018, and ended on April 30, 2019, with the exception of Mauritius and the Seychelles, for which it ended on May 15, 2019. Tropical cyclones also existed outside the conventional bounds of the season, however, with Moderate Tropical Storm 01 in September and the remnants of Tropical Cyclone Lorna in May.\n\n==Systems==\n===Moderate Tropical Storm 01===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=01R 2018-09-16 0920Z.jpg\n|Track=01R 2018 track.png\n|Formed=September 13\n|Dissipated=September 17\n|10-min winds=40\n|1-min winds=45\n|Pressure=1004\n}}\nOn September 11, a disturbance formed in the open waters of Indian Ocean. On the next day, the system intensified to a tropical depression formed to the southwest of [[Diego Garcia]].<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201809140600_1_1_20182019.pdf (in French)</ref> The system tracked west-southwestward, organizing slowly over marginally warm waters of 26\u201327 degrees Celsius and moderate wind shear.<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201809150600_3_1_20182019.pdf (in French)</ref> On September 16, the tropical depression began to quickly weaken after encountering unfavorable conditions. On the next day, both the MFR and the JTWC issued their final warnings, and the system was downgraded to an extratropical low. The remains of the system dissipated a few ours later north of [[Madagascar]].<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201809170600_7_1_20182019.pdf (in French)</ref> In post-storm analysis, the system was upgraded into a moderate tropical storm, although it remained unnamed.<ref>{{cite web|language=French|publisher=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France|year=2018|accessdate=November 8, 2018|title=Saisons cycloniques archiv\u00e9es: Temp\u00eate Tropicale Mod\u00e9r\u00e9e 01|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/data/20182019/2018RE01.html}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Alcide===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Alcide 2018-11-08 0656Z.jpg\n|Track=Alcide 2018 track.png\n|Formed=November 5\n|Dissipated=November 12\n|10-min winds=90\n|1-min winds=100\n|Pressure=965\n}}\nOn November 6, a tropical depression formed well to the east-northeast of Madagascar.<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811060600_1_2_20182019.pdf (in French)</ref> The system continued to track generally west-southwestward into more favorable conditions for the next few hours, before strengthening into a Moderate Tropical Storm and was named Alcide later that day.<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811061800_ALCIDE.pdf (in French)</ref> On November 7 at 06:00 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]], Alcide strengthened into a tropical cyclone, or a Category 1-equivalent tropical cyclone on the [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale|Saffir\u2013Simpson hurricane wind scale]] (SSHWS)<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811070600_ALCIDE.pdf (in French)</ref> On November 8 at 06:00 UTC, Alcide strengthened into an intense tropical cyclone, or a Category 3-equivalent tropical cyclone on the SSHWS, with maximum 10-minute sustained winds of {{convert|90|kn||round=5}} and a minimum central pressure of 965 hPa(mbar).<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811080600_ALCIDE.pdf (in French)</ref> It was downgraded to a tropical cyclone 6 hours later, mostly due to cooler sea temperatures and generally less favorable conditions.<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811081200_ALCIDE.pdf (in French)</ref> Alcide continued to weaken as it began an [[Anticyclone|anticyclonic]] loop east of the northern tip of Madagascar, falling to tropical storm status at 12:00 UTC on November 9.<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811091200_ALCIDE.pdf (in French)</ref> The system rapidly deteriorated thereafter, falling to tropical depression status at 00:00 UTC on November 11; Meteo-France discontinued advisories at noon that day.<ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811110000_EX-ALCIDE.pdf (in French)</ref><ref>http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811111200_EX-ALCIDE.pdf (in French)</ref>\nThe system continued east as a remnant low until November 13, when the remaining convection vanished, due to wind shear.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Severe Tropical Storm Bouchra===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Bouchra 2018-11-11 0650Z.jpg\n|Track=Bouchra 2018 track.png\n|Formed=November 9 <small>([[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Low Bouchra|Entered basin]])</small>\n|Dissipated=November 19\n|10-min winds=50\n|1-min winds=55\n|Pressure=990\n}}\nA weak low-pressure system developed in the equatorial [[Indian Ocean]] in M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France's area of responsibility on November 1 and moved slowly eastwards over the following few days while showing little signs of intensification.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/australia/charts/archive/index.shtml|title=12 UTC Gradient Level Wind Analysis Chart|last=|first=|date=1 November 2018|website=Bureau of Meteorology|access-date=}}</ref> Late on November 9, as the developing precursor depression to [[Cyclone Gaja|Severe Cyclonic Storm Gaja]] in the [[Bay of Bengal]] moved further away and the competing low-level airflow convergence associated with it diminished,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_201811091043.pdf|title=Tropical Activity Bulletin|last=|first=|date=9 November 2018|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France La R\u00e9union|access-date=}}</ref> the system's structure organised sufficiently to be classified as a tropical disturbance by M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://files.meteofrance.com/files/cyclone/SWI$03_20182019.png|title=Moderate Tropical Storm Bouchra Forecast Track Map|date=10 November 2018|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France La R\u00e9union|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111000309/http://files.meteofrance.com/files/cyclone/SWI$03_20182019.png|archive-date=11 November 2018|url-status=}}</ref> Very shortly afterwards, the system crossed the [[90th meridian east]] and entered the [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season|Australian region]], where it was classified by TCWC Jakarta as a tropical depression on November 10 local time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://meteo.bmkg.go.id/siklon|title=Current Tropical Cyclone Basin Activity|date=10 November 2018|website=Meteorology, Climatology and Geophysical Agency|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023110636/http://meteo.bmkg.go.id/siklon|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Later the same day, the JTWC assessed the developing low as having attained tropical storm status on the [[Saffir\u2013Simpson scale|Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale]], and assigned the system the unofficial designation 04S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metoc.navy.mil/jtwc/products/sh0419web.txt|title=Tropical Cyclone 04S Warning #1|date=10 November 2018|website=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110120059/http://www.metoc.navy.mil/jtwc/products/sh0419web.txt|archive-date=10 November 2018|url-status=}}</ref> A few hours later, at 10:00 UTC, the system moved back westwards and returned to the South-West Indian Ocean basin,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_201811101159.pdf|title=Tropical Activity Bulletin|last=|first=|date=10 November 2018|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France La R\u00e9union|access-date=}}</ref> where it gained the name 'Bouchra' from M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France and underwent a twelve-hour phase of rapid intensification to [[Tropical cyclone scales#South-Western Indian Ocean|severe tropical storm]] status.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811110000_BOUCHRA.pdf|title=Bouchra Analysis Bulletin #2|last=|first=|date=11 November 2018|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France La R\u00e9union|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOver the following days, Bouchra fought increasingly unfavorable atmospheric conditions, and underwent a gradual weakening trend.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201811111200_BOUCHRA.pdf|title=Tropical Storm Bouchra Advisory (12 UTC)|last=|first=|date=11 November 2018|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France La R\u00e9union|access-date=14 November 2018}}</ref> During this time, the cyclone proceeded to track in a slow cyclonic loop just to the west of the border of the Australian region in weak overall steering influences, and was often quasi-stationary.<ref name=\":0\" /> After meandering here for a number of days, the system re-entered the Australian region late on November 12.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_201811131156.pdf|title=Tropical Activity Bulletin|last=|first=|date=13 November 2018|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France La R\u00e9union|access-date=13 November 2018}}</ref> By this stage, the system had weakened significantly from its peak intensity, and was only at tropical depression strength.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/nwcyclone.shtml|title=Western Region Tropical Cyclone Outlook|date=13 November 2018|website=Bureau of Meteorology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113132217/http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/nwcyclone.shtml|archive-date=13 November 2018|url-status=|access-date=13 November 2018}}</ref> The period of residence in the Australian basin proved to be short-lived once again, however, with M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France indicating that Ex-Tropical Storm Bouchra had returned to the far eastern part of their area of responsibility early on November 13.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the early hours of November 14, the [[Bureau of Meteorology|Australian Bureau of Meteorology]] noted that the system had crossed back into the Australian region basin.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/nwcyclone.shtml|title=Western Region Tropical Cyclone Outlook|date=14 November 2018|website=Bureau of Meteorology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114025621/http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/nwcyclone.shtml|archive-date=14 November 2018|url-status=|access-date=14 November 2018}}</ref> However, on November 17, Bouchra crossed back over into the South-West Indian Ocean basin, as the storm began taking a southwestward trajectory.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Kenanga===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Kenanga 2018-12-19 0815Z.jpg\n|Track=Kenanga 2018 track.png\n|Formed=December 16 <small>([[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Kenanga|Entered basin]])</small>\n|Dissipated=December 22\n|10-min winds=100\n|1-min winds=115\n|Pressure=942\n}}\n{{cn span|text=On December 14, a tropical low formed well southwest of [[Sumatra]] in the [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season|Australian region basin]]. It slowly strengthened and on the next day, the system was officially named ''Kenanga'' as it tracked roughly southwestward. Continuing on this course, Kenanga entered the South-West Indian basin on December 16. On the next day, the system quickly intensified into an [[Intense Tropical Cyclone|intense tropical cyclone]], and Kenaga maintained this intensity for another day. The storm reached peak intensity on December 17, with 10-minute sustained wind speeds of {{convert|115|mph|km/h}}, and a minimum central pressure of 942 mbar (hPa). On the morning of the next day, the system encountered high wind shear and started weakening, and Kenanga was downgraded to a Moderate Tropical Storm by the evening of that day. The system was finally downgraded to an extratropical low on December 19. On the next day, Kenanga re-intensified into tropical depression. On December 22, Kenanga lost its remaining convection and dissipated. The system did not affect any land areas, and caused no damage or fatalities.|date=May 2019}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Cilida===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Cilida 2018-12-21 0640Z.jpg\n|Track=Cilida 2018 track.png\n|Formed=December 16\n|Dissipated=December 24\n|10-min winds=115\n|1-min winds=130 <!--Retroactively downgraded per https://www.nrlmry.navy.mil/tcdat/tc19/SHEM/07S.CILIDA/trackfile.txt-->\n|Pressure=940\n}}\nOn December 16, Meteo-France tracked a low-pressure area inside an area of possible tropical cyclone development. While tracking southwest, it then intensified to tropical storm status and then cyclone status. On December 23, it passed east of [[Mauritius]], bringing beneficial rainfall and gusting winds that knocked down tree branches. It then turned southeast and weakened, later dissipating in the far southern reaches of the basin.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Le Express|title=Cilida: un petit tour puis s\u2019en va|date=December 23, 2018|accessdate=January 3, 2019|url=https://www.lexpress.mu/article/344884/cilida-un-petit-tour-puis-sen-va}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=Mauritius Broadcasting Corporation|date=December 25, 2018|author=Shabneeze Oozeear|accessdate=January 3, 2019|title=Cilida : les pluies apport\u00e9es par le cyclone b\u00e9n\u00e9fique aux plantations|url=https://www.mbcradio.tv/article/cilida-les-pluies-apport\u00e9es-par-le-cyclone-b\u00e9n\u00e9fique-aux-plantations}}</ref> \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Moderate Tropical Storm Desmond===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Desmond 2019-01-20 1115Z.jpg\n|Track=Desmond 2019 track.png\n|Formed=January 17\n|Dissipated=January 22\n|10-min winds=35\n|1-min winds=40\n|Pressure=995\n}}\n{{expand section|date=February 2019}}\nA tropical depression formed near the east coast of [[Mozambique]] on January 17. During the next couple of days, the storm made a counterclockwise loop towards the west, before turning northward. The system intensified into a moderate tropical storm on January 19 and was named ''Desmond''. The system gradually intensified as it drifted northward. The storm reached peak intensity on January 20, as a moderate tropical storm with 10-minute sustained winds of 65&nbsp;km/h (40 mph) wind and a minimum central pressure of 995 mbar. On the next day, Desmond made landfall in [[Mozambique]]. Afterward, the storm rapidly weakened and was downgraded to a remnant low on January 22. Later that day, Desmond turned eastward back towards the coast, while continuing to weaken. A few hours later, Desmond lost all of its remaining convection and dissipated.<ref>{{cite news|author=H\u00e9lia Chopo|url=http://opais.sapo.mz/mais-de-400-familias-afectadas-pela-tempestade-desmond-em-sofala|title=Mais de 400 fam\u00edlias afectadas pela tempestade \"Desmond\" em Sofala|language=Portuguese|publisher=O PA\u00cdS|date=January 23, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> The system dissipated on January 22. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Moderate Tropical Storm Eketsang===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Eketsang 2019-01-24 1050Z.jpg\n|Track=Eketsang 2019 track.png\n|Formed=January 22\n|Dissipated=January 24\n|10-min winds=40\n|1-min winds=\n|Pressure=993\n}}\n{{expand section|date=February 2019}}\nA disturbance formed over [[Madagascar]] on January 21. On the next day, the storm emerged into the Mozambique Channel and organized into a tropical depression. On January 23, the system strengthened into a moderate tropical storm and was named Eketsang. The system tracked southwestward while strengthening, reaching its peak intensity later that day, with 10-minute sustained winds of 75&nbsp;km/h(45 mph) and a minimum central pressure of 993 mbar. On the same day, the storm turned to the southeast, back towards Madagascar. On January 24, the storm curved around the south coast of Madagascar and weakened into a subtropical depression. Afterward, the storm began accelerating southeastward, before dissipating on January 26. 27 deaths were reported from the storm, and 1 person went missing, mostly due to landslides.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cycloneoi.com/archives-blog/infos-diverses/madagascar-27-morts-suite-au-fortes-pluies-et-a-la-tempete-eketsang.html|title=Madagascar : 27 morts suite au fortes pluies et \u00e0 la Temp\u00eate EKETSANG|language=French|publisher=Cyclone Ocean Indien|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Funani===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Funani 2019-02-07 0915Z.jpg\n|Track=Funani 2019 track.png\n|Formed=February 3\n|Dissipated=February 10\n|10-min winds=105\n|1-min winds=115\n|Pressure=940\n}}\n{{expand section|date=February 2019}}\nOn February 2, a disturbance formed in the open [[Indian Ocean]]. The system in countered favorable conditions and began to  rapidly intensified, reaching moderate tropical storm status on February 3 and further intensified into an intense tropical cyclone the next day. The storm recurved east and degan to move southwestwards. The system accelerated as it moved into an area of low sea surface temperature on February 7. The next day, it was downgraded to moderate tropical storm two days later. The storm transitioned to an [[Extratropical cyclone]] on February 10 before dissipating later that day.<ref>{{cite news|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019|title=Cyclone Funani : Air Mauritius annule six vols de Rodrigues|language=French|publisher=Le Mauricien|url=https://www.lemauricien.com/article/cyclone-funani-air-mauritius-annule-six-vols-de-rodrigues/}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Gelena===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Gelena 2019-02-09 0627Z.jpg\n|Track=Gelena 2019 track.png\n|Formed=February 4\n|Dissipated=February 14 ([[2018-19 Australian region cyclone season#Other systems|Exited basin]])\n|10-min winds=110\n|1-min winds=120\n|Pressure=942\n}}\n{{Expand section|date=February 2019}}\nGelena was the second storm to affect the island of [[Rodrigues]] in a week, following Intense Tropical Cyclone Funani. Gelena brought strong winds that destroyed 90% of the [[electric grid]] on the island.<ref>{{cite news|last=Whitfield|first=Kate|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1085093/Mauritius-cyclone-satellite-tracker-Rodrigues-Cyclone-Gelena-charts-latest-update|title=Mauritius cyclone satellite tracker: Rodrigues SMASHED by Cyclone Gelena - SHOCK charts|publisher=Daily Express|date=February 10, 2019|access-date=February 11, 2019}}</ref> Overall damage on the island were about US$1&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Austin|first=Nick|url=https://www.freightwaves.com/news/weather/small-island-damaged-by-second-cyclone-this-year|title=Small island damaged by second cyclone this year|publisher=FreightWaves|date=March 28, 2019|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Haleh===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Haleh 2019-03-04 0858Z.jpg\n|Track=Haleh 2019 track.png\n|Formed=February 28\n|Dissipated=March 7\n|10-min winds=95\n|1-min winds=115\n|Pressure=945\n}}\n{{cn span|text=On February 28, Tropical Depression 10 formed in the south central Indian Ocean, south of the [[Maldives]]. On March 2, the system strengthened into Moderate Tropical Storm Haleh, before intensifying further into a severe tropical storm later that day. On March 3, Haleh intensified into a tropical cyclone. Finding itself in favourable conditions, Haleh continued to intensify and reached its peak intensity on March 4, as a Category 4-equivalent intense tropical cyclone, with 1-minute sustained winds of 215&nbsp;km/h (130&nbsp;mph). On March 5, Haleh meandered into hostile conditions with low sea surface ocean heat content and medium vertical wind shear, and the system weakened back to a Category 1 tropical cyclone. Haleh gradually weakened over the next couple of days, eventually degenerating into a post-tropical low late on March 7.|date=May 2019}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Idai===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Idai 2019-03-14 1135Z.jpg\n|Track=Idai 2019 track.png\n|Formed=March 4\n|Dissipated=March 16\n|10-min winds=105\n|1-min winds=110\n|Pressure=940\n}}\n{{Main|Cyclone Idai}}\nTropical Depression 11 formed off the east coast of Mozambique on March 4. Afterward, the tropical depression drifted northeastward very slowly, making landfall on Mozambique later that day. On March 6, Tropical Depression 11 was given a yellow tropical cyclone development warning by the [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] (JTWC). On March 7, the storm turned west-southwestward, while continuing to retain its tropical identity overland. On March 8, Tropical Depression 11 weakened and turned back towards the east. Early on March 9, the tropical depression emerged into the [[Mozambique Channel]] and began to organize. On the same day, the JTWC stated that the system had a high probability for genesis into a tropical cyclone, and later on the same day, the system strengthened into a moderate tropical storm and received the name ''Idai''. On March 10, Idai began to rapidly intensify, strengthening into a tropical cyclone near Madagascar, and the system made yet another turn westward, moving to the southwest. On the next day, the storm intensified into the seventh intense tropical cyclone of the season, and soon reached its peak intensity as a Category 3-equivalent tropical cyclone. On March 12, Idai began to weaken, as the system underwent an [[eyewall replacement cycle]]. On March 13, Idai began accelerating westward. At 00:00 UTC on March 15, the MFR reported that Idai had made landfall near [[Beira, Mozambique]], with 10-minute sustained winds of 165 km/h (105 mph).<ref>{{cite web |title=Intense Tropical Cyclone Idai Warning 26 |url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSA_201903150000_IDAI.pdf |publisher=Meteo France La Reunion |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315030814/http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSA_201903150000_IDAI.pdf|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=15 March 2019|archivedate=15 March 2019}}</ref> Idai quickly weakened after landfall, degenerating into a tropical depression later that day. Afterward, Idai slowly moved inland while dumping large amounts of rain, resulting in [[flash flood|flash flooding]]. Late on March 16, Idai degenerated into a remnant low, but the storm's remnant continued dumping rain across the region. On March 17, Idai's remnant turned eastward once again, eventually re-emerging into the Mozambique Channel a second time on March 19. On March 21, Idai's remnants dissipated.<ref name=\"March 22 cyclone bulletin\">{{cite web |url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITA_201903210928.pdf |title=Bulletin for Cyclonic Activity and Significant Tropical Weather in the Southwest Indian Ocean|publisher=Meteo France La Reunion |date=21 March 2019|accessdate=23 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323014610/http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITA_201903210928.pdf|archivedate=23 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"March 23 cyclone bulletin\">{{cite web |url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITA_201903220958.pdf |title=Bulletin for Cyclonic Activity and Significant Tropical Weather in the Southwest Indian Ocean|publisher=Meteo France La Reunion |date=22 March 2019|accessdate=23 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323014717/http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITA_201903220958.pdf|archivedate=23 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a tropical depression, Idai affected [[Malawi]] and [[Mozambique]], during its first landfall. At least 56&nbsp;people died, and 577 others were injured due to flooding in Malawi. About 83,000&nbsp;people were displaced. The southern districts of [[Chikwawa District|Chikwawa]] and [[Nsanje District|Nsanje]] became isolated by floodwaters.<ref>{{cite news|last=Phiri|first=Frank|publisher=Reuters|date=March 13, 2019|accessdate=March 13, 2019|title=Malawi flooding death toll rises to 56, braced for Cyclone Idai|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-malawi-floods/malawi-flooding-death-toll-rises-to-56-braced-for-cyclone-idai-idUSKBN1QU1MS}}</ref> In Mozambique, 66&nbsp;people were killed by the flooding, and affected 141,000&nbsp;people. The Council of Ministers required 1.1&nbsp;billion [[metical]] (US$17.6&nbsp;million) to help those who were affected by the flooding.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/story/624800/Floods-kill-66-in-Mozambique|title=Floods kill 66 in Mozambique|publisher=Gulf Times|date=March 13, 2019|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}</ref> In total, Idai killed at least 1,297 people and left thousands more missing, becoming one of the deadliest tropical cyclones in the modern history of [[Africa]] and the [[Southern Hemisphere]] as a whole.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Funes |first1=Yessenia |title=Cyclone Idai Poised to Become Southern Hemisphere\u2019s Deadliest Tropical Storm, With More Than 1,000 Feared Dead |url=https://earther.gizmodo.com/cyclone-idai-poised-to-become-southern-hemisphere-s-dea-1833406709 |publisher=Earther |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alan Yuhas|newspaper=New York Times|date=19 March 2019|accessdate=19 March 2019|title=Cyclone Idai May Be \u2018One of the Worst\u2019 Disasters in the Southern Hemisphere|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/19/world/africa/cyclone-idai-mozambique.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Zenaida Machado|publisher=Human Rights Watch|date=3 April 2019|accessdate=3 April 2019|title=Thousands Missing in Mozambique Following Cyclone Idai|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/04/03/thousands-missing-mozambique-following-cyclone-idai}}</ref>{{EM-DAT}} With this death toll, Idai is the deadliest tropical cyclone recorded in the South-West Indian Ocean basin, and the second-deadliest tropical cyclone overall in the [[Southern Hemisphere]], behind only [[Cyclone Flores]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Masters |first1=Jeff |title=Africa\u2019s Hurricane Katrina: Tropical Cyclone Idai Causes an Extreme Catastrophe |url=https://www.wunderground.com/cat6/Africas-Hurricane-Katrina-Tropical-Cyclone-Idai-Causes-Extreme-Catastrophe |website=Weather Underground |accessdate=23 March 2019}}</ref> In addition, the total damages from the cyclone are expected to exceed US$2&nbsp;billion (2019 USD), which would make Idai the costliest cyclone on record in the basin.<ref name=\"damages at 2 billion\">{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/cyclone-idai-damages-estimated-2-billion-world-bank-151558889.html|title=Cyclone Idai damages estimated at $2 billion: World Bank|author=|publisher=Yahoo Finance|date=12 April 2019|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"devastation\">{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/africa/1596668/cyclone-idai-death-toll-passes-1000-with-damage-to-cost-billions/|title=One month later: Cyclone Idai\u2019s devastation by the numbers|author=Lynsey Chutel|publisher=Quartz Africa|date=16 April 2019|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Savannah===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Savannah 2019-03-17 0724Z.jpg\n|Track=Savannah 2019 track.png\n|Formed=March 17 <small>([[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Savannah|entered basin]])</small>\n|Dissipated=March 19\n|10-min winds=90\n|1-min winds=95\n|Pressure=962\n}}\n{{main|Cyclone Savannah}}\nOn March 17, Severe Tropical Cyclone Savannah crossed over from the [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season|Australian region basin]] into the South-West Indian basin, shortly after reaching its peak intensity. Savannah was classified as an intense tropical cyclone on the [[Tropical cyclone scales#South-West Indian Ocean|South-West Indian Ocean scale]] after it entered the basin. Savannah weakened soon after reaching its peak intensity. On March 19, Savannah transitioned into a post-tropical cyclone, with the system continuing southwestward. On the next day, Savannah's remnant looped eastward, before turning westward on March 21. The system weakened afterward, with Savannah's remnant dissipating on March 23. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Joaninha===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Joaninha 2019-03-27 0925Z.jpg\n|Track=Joaninha 2019 track.png\n|Formed=March 18\n|Dissipated=March 30\n|10-min winds=100\n|1-min winds=115\n|Pressure=939\n}}\nOn March 18, Tropical Depression 13 formed to the east of Madagascar. After a few days of meandering to the west and then the southeast, the system intensified into Moderate Tropical Storm Joaninha on March 22, turning southward as it did so. On March 23, Joaninha strengthened into a severe tropical storm. Early on March 24, Joaninha strengthened further into a tropical cyclone on the MFR scale. On the next day, Joaninha intensified into an intense tropical cyclone. After moving over cooler waters, Joaninha slowly began to weaken, dropping to severe tropical storm intensity on the MFR scale on March 29. On March 30, Joaninha became post-tropical, shortly after merging with an upper-level low.\n\nJoaninha passed within approximately 80&nbsp;km&nbsp;(50&nbsp;mi) of the [[Mauritius|Mauritian]] island of [[Rodrigues]], producing wind gusts on the northern side of the island at [[Port Mathurin]] up to 161&nbsp;km/h&nbsp;(100&nbsp;mph), including gusts in excess of 100&nbsp;km/h&nbsp;(60&nbsp;mph) for 33 hours. Nearly 200&nbsp;mm&nbsp;(8&nbsp;in) of rain fell across the island during the passage of the system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/tropical-cyclone-joaninha-slams-indian-ocean-island-rodrigues-190327091423484.html|title=Tropical Cyclone Joaninha slams Indian Ocean island of Rodrigues|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> The system damaged about 100 homes in [[Rodrigues]] causing $10.5 million in damages.{{cn|date=June 2019}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Intense Tropical Cyclone Kenneth===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Kenneth 2019-04-25 0745Z.jpg\n|Track=Kenneth 2019 track.png\n|Formed=April 21\n|Dissipated=April 29\n|10-min winds=115\n|1-min winds=125\n|Pressure=934\n}}\n{{main|Cyclone Kenneth}}\nOn April 21, M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France (MFR) initiated advisories on Tropical Disturbance 14, which was situated to the northeast of Madagascar. The system drifted westward, organizing as it did so. Early on April 23, the system strengthened into a tropical depression. Later that day, at 12:00 UTC, the tropical depression strengthened into a moderate tropical storm as was named ''Kenneth'', becoming the fourteenth tropical storm of the season. Early on April 24, Kenneth strengthened into a tropical cyclone. Kenneth rapidly organized while approaching Mozambique, reaching Category 3-equivalent tropical cyclone intensity within several hours.<ref>{{cite report |title=Tropical Cyclone 24S (Kenneth) Warning 008 |url=https://www.wis-jma.go.jp/d/o/PGTW/Alphanumeric/Warning/Tropical_cyclone/20190424/210000/A_WTXS31PGTW242100_C_RJTD_20190424202631_29.txt |website=Joint Typhoon Warning Center |publisher=Naval Meteorology and Oceanography Command |accessdate=24 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424210552/https://www.wis-jma.go.jp/d/o/PGTW/Alphanumeric/Warning/Tropical_cyclone/20190424/210000/A_WTXS31PGTW242100_C_RJTD_20190424202631_29.txt |archivedate=24 April 2019 |date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |title=Intense Tropical Cyclone 14 (Kenneth): Warning 10 |url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSA_201904250000_KENNETH.pdf |website=Meteo France la Reunion |accessdate=25 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425130422/http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSA_201904250000_KENNETH.pdf |archivedate=25 April 2019 |date=25 April 2019}}</ref> On the same day, Kenneth was projected to strike Mozambique within a day and bring more flooding and wind damage to the nation, about a month after Cyclone Idai had devastated the region, raising fears that the ongoing humanitarian crisis there could be worsened by the storm.<ref name=\"humanitarian crisis\">{{cite web|url=https://weather.com/storms/hurricane/news/2019-04-24-tropical-cyclone-kenneth-forecast-mozambique|title=Tropical Cyclone Kenneth to Bring Feet of Rain, Damaging Winds to Mozambique Weeks After Idai Brings Humanitarian Crisis|author=Jonathan Belles|publisher=The Weather Company|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"taking aim\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/24/africa/storm-kenneth-mozambique-intl/index.html|title=Another tropical cyclone is taking aim at storm-wrecked Mozambique|author1=Brandon Miller|author2=Bukola Adebayo|publisher=Cable News Network|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> On the next day, Kenneth reached its peak intensity, becoming a Category 4-equivalent intense tropical cyclone, as the storm began to near landfall in Mozambique. However, at about that time, Kenneth initiated an [[eyewall replacement cycle]] and gradually began to weaken, just prior to landfall. Later that day, at 18:15 UTC, Kenneth made landfall as a Category 4-equivalent intense tropical cyclone in Mozambique, with 1-minute sustained winds of 220&nbsp;km/h (140&nbsp;mph), just north of [[Pemba, Mozambique|Pemba]].<ref name=\"humanitarian crisis\" /> This made Kenneth the most intense landfalling storm in Mozambique's recorded history.<ref name=\"thousands evacuated\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/25/africa/cyclone-kenneth-mozambique-evacuation-intl/index.html|title=Cyclone Kenneth: Thousands evacuated as Mozambique is hit with the strongest storm in its history|author=Brandon Miller|publisher=Cable News Network|date=25 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Kenneth's landfall also marked the second time in Mozambique's recorded history in which two storms have made landfall during the same season at tropical cyclone intensity or higher.<ref name=\"tens of thousands\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/04/cyclone-kenneth-begins-landfall-northern-mozambique-190425182138888.html|title=Tens of thousands evacuated as Cyclone Kenneth hits Mozambique|author=|publisher=Al-Jazeera News|date=25 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nKenneth underwent extremely rapid weakening upon making landfall, despite the relatively favorable atmospheric environment and flat terrain of northern Mozambique. The system's maximum ten-minute sustained winds decreased from 205 km/h (125 mph) to just 65 km/h (40 mph) in just ten hours after landfall, weakening the storm to tropical storm intensity.<ref>{{cite report |title=Overland Depression 14 (Ex-Kenneth): Warning 14 |url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSA_201904260000_EX-KENNETH.pdf |website=Meteo France la Reunion |accessdate=26 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426020013/http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSA_201904260000_EX-KENNETH.pdf |archivedate=26 April 2019 |date=26 April 2019}}</ref> On April 26, Kenneth weakened to tropical depression intensity, while continuing its southward motion. On April 27, Kenneth began drifting northward, also developing some thunderstorms off the coast of Mozambique.<ref>{{cite report |title=Bulletin for Cyclonic Activity and Significant Tropical Weather in the Southwest Indian Ocean |url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITA_201904271034.pdf |website=Meteo France la Reunion |accessdate=27 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427170838/http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITA_201904271034.pdf |archivedate=27 April 2019 |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> Kenneth continued to weaken, dissipating by 12:00 UTC on April 29.<ref>{{cite report |title=Bulletin for Cyclonic Activity and Significant Tropical Weather in the Southwest Indian Ocean |url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITA_201904291056.pdf |website=Meteo France la Reunion |accessdate=30 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430210109/http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/anglais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITA_201904291056.pdf |archivedate=30 April 2019 |date=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nKenneth killed at least 52 people; seven on the island of [[Comoros]],<ref name=\"Comoros report 2\">{{cite web |title=Comoros: Humanitarian Situation Report No #2 - Cyclone Kenneth |url=https://reliefweb.int/report/comoros/comoros-humanitarian-situation-report-no-2-cyclone-kenneth |website=Relief Web |publisher=UN Children's Fund |accessdate=28 April 2019 |date=25 April 2019}}</ref> and at least 45 people in Mozambique.<ref>{{cite web |title=Southern Africa: Tropical Cyclone Kenneth Flash Update No. 13 (12 May 2019) |url=https://reliefweb.int/report/mozambique/southern-africa-tropical-cyclone-kenneth-flash-update-no-13-12-may-2019 |website=Relief Web |publisher=UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs |accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"roars through\">{{cite web |last1=Aaro |first1=David |title=Cyclone Kenneth roars through Mozambique, kills at least 5 |url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/cyclone-kenneth-roars-through-mozambique-kills-at-least-5 |website=Fox News |publisher=Fox News Network |accessdate=28 April 2019 |date=27 April 2019}}</ref> In Mozambique, Kenneth caused widespread damage in the city of Pemba, including extensive power outages and numerous felled trees.<ref name=\"storm-battered\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-48050859 |title=Cyclone Kenneth: Storm-battered Mozambique hit again |website=BBC News |date=25 April 2019 |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Kenneth is estimated to have caused at least $100 million in damages.<ref name=\"April 2019 report\">{{cite report |title=Global Catastrophe Recap April 2019 |url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20190508-analytics-if-april-global-recap.pdf |website=AON Benfield |accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> \n{{clear}}\n\n===Tropical Cyclone Lorna===\n{{Infobox tropical cyclone small\n|Basin=SWI\n|Image=Lorna 2019-04-28 0747Z.jpg\n|Track=Lorna 2019 track.png\n|Formed=April 21\n|Dissipated=May 1\n|10-min winds=80\n|1-min winds=75\n|Pressure=964\n}}\nOn April 21, Tropical Depression 15 formed to the southeast of the [[Maldives]]. The system moved southeastward, before turning south-southeastward on April 22, while slowly strengthening. On the next day, the system intensified into Moderate Tropical Storm Lorna, making the 2018\u201319 season the most active cyclone season recorded in the South-West Indian Ocean in the satellite era, surpassing the previous record set by the [[1993\u201394 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season|1993\u201394 season]]. Lorna resumed a southeasterly direction on April 24, while continuing to organise. On April 25, Lorna then intensified into a severe tropical storm. On the same day, Lorna began to [[Fujiwhara effect|interact]] with a smaller [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Low|tropical low]] to the east, in the Australian region basin, before absorbing the weaker system early on the next day.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metoc.navy.mil/jtwc/products/abioweb.txt|title=Indian Ocean Tropical Weather Advisory|date=25 April 2019|website=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426010744/https://www.metoc.navy.mil/jtwc/products/abioweb.txt|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/nwcyclone.shtml|title=Western Region Tropical Cyclone Outlook|date=26 April 2019|website=Bureau of Meteorology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426082653/http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/nwcyclone.shtml|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=26 April 2019}}</ref> On April 26, the JTWC upgraded Lorna to Category 1 status, while Lorna began turning towards the south. Soon afterward, Lorna encountered relatively strong vertical wind shear and steadily decreasing sea temperatures as it continued to track southwards, causing its gradual intensification trend to halt, and the JTWC to downgrade the system to a high-end tropical storm.\n\nOn 28 April, somewhat unexpectedly, and contradicting forecasts by MFR and the JTWC, the system developed a clearly defined eye and underwent steady intensification. Consequently, MFR upgraded the system to a tropical cyclone, and the JTWC upgraded Lorna to Category 1 status on the Saffir\u2013Simpson scale for the second time. Around this time, Lorna deviated from its predominantly southwards motion, and assumed a track to the south-southeast. Due to the system being located on the very eastern edge of the South-West Indian Ocean basin during the previous two days, this slight easterly motion caused the cyclone to become centred directly over the [[90th meridian east]]\u2014the boundary of the Australian Bureau of Meteorology's area of responsibility. Lorna strengthened to peak intensity while tracking southwards along the boundary between the two regions, attaining ten-minute sustained winds of 150 km/h (90 mph) by 18:00 UTC on April 28.\n\nBy 29 April, the structure of the cyclone had degraded significantly, primarily due to strong vertical wind shear and resulting dry air intrusion.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201904290600_LORNA.pdf|title=Tropical Cyclone Analysis Bulletin #26 (Lorna)|last=|first=|date=29 April 2019|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France|language=French|access-date=29 April 2019}}</ref> As a result, the system was downgraded by the MFR to a severe tropical storm.<ref name=\":3\" /> Very strong vertical wind shear, analysed at 40 knots (75 km/h; 45 mph) at 09:00 UTC on April 29,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/cmrs/CMRSF_201904291200_EX-LORNA.pdf|title=Tropical Cyclone Analysis Bulletin #27 (Lorna)|last=|first=|date=29 April 2019|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France|language=French|access-date=29 April 2019}}</ref> caused Lorna to become devoid of deep convection later that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metoc.navy.mil/jtwc/products/sh2519web.txt|title=Tropical Cyclone Warning #24 (Lorna)|date=29 April 2019|website=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429131720/https://www.metoc.navy.mil/jtwc/products/sh2519web.txt|archive-date=29 April 2019|url-status=|access-date=29 April 2019}}</ref> Having lost tropical characteristics, the system was downgraded by the MFR at 12:00 UTC to a powerful [[Beaufort scale|storm-force]] [[Post-tropical cyclone|post-tropical depression]]. Gale-force winds ceased by 12:00 UTC on April 30,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_201904301007.pdf|title=South-West Indian Ocean Cyclonic Activity Bulletin|last=|first=|date=30 April 2019|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France|access-date=30 April 2019}}</ref> and Ex-Tropical Cyclone Lorna exited the basin into the Australian region by 06:00 UTC on May 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/whighseas.shtml|title=Western Area High Seas Forecast (11Z)|date=1 May 2019|website=Bureau of Meteorology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501113323/http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/whighseas.shtml|archive-date=1 May 2019|url-status=|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meteo.fr/temps/domtom/La_Reunion/webcmrs9.0/francais/activiteope/bulletins/zcit/ZCITF_201905011109.pdf|title=South-West Indian Ocean Cyclone Activity Bulletin|last=|first=|date=1 May 2019|website=M\u00e9t\u00e9o-France|language=French|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref> Soon afterward, Lorna became an extratropical low,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/whighseas.shtml|title=Western Area High Seas Forecast (23Z)|date=1 May 2019|website=Bureau of Meteorology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502023459/http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/whighseas.shtml|archive-date=2 May 2019|url-status=|access-date=2 May 2019}}</ref> before merging with another low-pressure system in the central southern Indian Ocean later that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/whighseas.shtml|title=Western Area High Seas Forecast (11Z)|date=1 May 2019|website=Bureau of Meteorology|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501113323/http://www.bom.gov.au/wa/forecasts/whighseas.shtml|archive-date=1 May 2019|url-status=|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Storm names==\nWithin the South-West Indian Ocean, tropical depressions and subtropical depressions that are judged to have 10-minute sustained windspeeds of 65&nbsp;km/h (40&nbsp;mph) by the [[Regional Specialized Meteorological Center]] on [[R\u00e9union|La R\u00e9union Island]], France (RSMC La R\u00e9union) are usually assigned a name. However, it is the Sub-Regional Tropical Cyclone Advisory Centers in Mauritius and Madagascar who name the systems. The Sub-Regional Tropical Cyclone Advisory Center in Mauritius names a storm should it intensify into a moderate tropical storm between [[55th meridian east|55\u00b0E]] and [[90th meridian east|90\u00b0E]]. If instead a cyclone intensifies into a moderate tropical storm between [[30th meridian east|30\u00b0E]] and [[55th meridian east|55\u00b0E]] then the Sub-Regional Tropical Cyclone Advisory Center in Madagascar assigns the appropriate name to the storm. Beginning from the 2016\u201317 season, name lists within the South-West Indian Ocean will be rotated on a triennial basis. Storm names are only used once, so any storm name used this year will be removed from rotation and replaced with a new name for the 2021\u201322 season. The unused names are expected to be reused in the list for the 2021\u201322 season.<ref name=\"TCOP-SWIO\">{{cite web|year=2016|title=Tropical Cyclone Operational Plan for the South-West Indian Ocean|accessdate=2016-10-05|author=Regional Association I Tropical Cyclone Committee|publisher=[[World Meteorological Organization]]|url=http://www.wmo.int/pages/prog/www/tcp/documents/OperationalPlan_TCP-12_WMO-1178_2016_En.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n{| width=\"90%\"\n|\n*Alcide\n*Bouchra\n*Cilida\n*Desmond\n*Eketsang\n*Funani\n*Gelena\n*Haleh\n*[[Cyclone Idai|Idai]]\n|\n*Joaninha\n*[[Cyclone Kenneth|Kenneth]]\n*Lorna\n*{{tcname unused|Maipelo}}\n*{{tcname unused|Njazi}}\n*{{tcname unused|Oscar}}\n*{{tcname unused|Pamela}}\n*{{tcname unused|Quentin}}\n*{{tcname unused|Rajab}}\n|\n*{{tcname unused|Savana}}\n*{{tcname unused|Themba}}\n*{{tcname unused|Uyapo}}\n*{{tcname unused|Viviane}}\n*{{tcname unused|Walter}}\n*{{tcname unused|Xangy}}\n*{{tcname unused|Yemurai}}\n*{{tcname unused|Zanele}}\n|}\n\nKenanga entered this basin as a moderate tropical storm from the [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season|Australian region]] on December 16, retaining its name assigned by [[Meteorology, Climatology, and Geophysical Agency|TCWC Jakarta]]. Similarly, [[Cyclone Savannah|Savannah]] entered this basin as an intense tropical cyclone from the Australian region on March 17, retaining its name assigned by [[Bureau of Meteorology|TCWC Perth]]. Furthermore, Moderate Tropical Storm 01 which formed in September was not assigned a name because it was not classified as a moderate tropical storm until the post-analysis was completed.\n\nAfter the season, the twelve names used were automatically retired and were replaced with ''Ana'', ''Batsirai'', ''Cliff'', ''Damako'', ''Emnati'', ''Fezile'', ''Gomba'', ''Halima'', ''Issa'', ''Jasmine'', ''Karim'' and ''Letlama'', respectively for the 2021\u201322 season.\n\n==Seasonal effects==\nThis table lists all of the tropical cyclones and subtropical cyclones that were monitored during the 2018\u20132019 South-West Indian Ocean cyclone season. Information on their intensity, duration, name, areas affected, primarily comes from RSMC La R\u00e9union. Death and damage reports come from either press reports or the relevant national disaster management agency while the damage totals are given in 2018 or 2019&nbsp;USD.\n\n{{Pacific areas affected (Top)}}\n|-\n| {{Sort|01|01}} || {{Sort|180913|September&nbsp;13&nbsp;\u2013 17}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|MTS}}|{{Sort|3|Moderate tropical storm}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|MTS}}|{{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|MTS}}|{{Sort|1004|1004&nbsp;hPa (29.65&nbsp;inHg)}} || None || {{ntsh|0}} None || {{ntsh|0}} None ||\n|-\n| {{Sort|02|Alcide}} || {{Sort|181105|November&nbsp;5&nbsp;\u2013 12}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|ITC}}|{{Sort|6|Intense tropical cyclone}} || bgcolor=#{{storm colour|ITC}}|{{Sort|165|165&nbsp;km/h (105&nbsp;mph)}} || bg